This... isn&#x27;t how lifetimes work.<p>As I said above, there&#x27;s no lifetime annotations you can use to ensure that y lives as long(aka is in the same scope) as x in the following<p><pre><code>  let x = 1;
  {
      let y = 2;
  }
</code></pre>
This is also true if you do dynamic allocations: there&#x27;s fundamentally no way to &quot;promote&quot; variables to a higher scopes just by using lifetime annotations.<p>Lifetimes are a purely passive thing, designed to allow the compiler to check the programmer&#x27;s use of references, <i>not</i> to allow the compiler to massage things around to ensure that whatever use work.<p>That is, if a Rust program compiles, then it will also compile (modulo needing extra `unsafe` annotation) and, importantly, do the same thing, if all the references are replaced with raw pointers, which don&#x27;t have lifetimes to describe their relationships.
